{
  "title": "Comprehensive Chemistry Guide",
  "topic": "Chapter: Solutions (Class 12)",
  "blocks": [
    {
      "type": "h1",
      "content": "Introduction to Solutions"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "A <b>solution</b> is a <span class=\"highlight\">homogeneous mixture</span> of two or more components. The component present in larger amount is called <b>solvent</b> and the one in smaller amount is called <b>solute</b>."
    },
    {
      "type": "h2",
      "content": "Types of Solutions"
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "ordered": false,
      "items": [
        "<b>Gaseous Solution:</b> Gas in gas (e.g., air)",
        "<b>Liquid Solution:</b> Solid/liquid/gas in liquid (e.g., salt in water)",
        "<b>Solid Solution:</b> Solid in solid (e.g., alloys like brass)"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "h2",
      "content": "Concentration of Solutions"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "Different ways to express concentration:"
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "ordered": false,
      "items": [
        "<b>Mass %:</b> $(\\frac{mass\\ of\\ solute}{mass\\ of\\ solution}) \\times 100$",
        "<b>Mole Fraction:</b> $X_A = \\frac{n_A}{n_A + n_B}$",
        "<b>Molarity (M):</b> $M = \\frac{n}{V(L)}$",
        "<b>Molality (m):</b> $m = \\frac{n}{mass\\ of\\ solvent\\ (kg)}$",
        "<b>ppm:</b> Parts per million for very dilute solutions"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "h2",
      "content": "Solubility"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "<b>Solubility</b> is the maximum amount of solute that dissolves in a given amount of solvent at a given temperature."
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "ordered": false,
      "items": [
        "Depends on nature of solute and solvent",
        "Temperature affects solubility",
        "Pressure affects gas solubility"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "h2",
      "content": "Henry's Law"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "Henry’s law states that the solubility of a gas in a liquid is directly proportional to the partial pressure of the gas."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "$p = k_H \\cdot x$"
    },
    {
      "type": "h3",
      "content": "Applications of Henry’s Law"
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "ordered": false,
      "items": [
        "Carbonated drinks (CO₂ dissolved under pressure)",
        "Scuba diving (avoid bends)",
        "High altitude breathing problems"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "h2",
      "content": "Raoult’s Law"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "The partial vapor pressure of each component is directly proportional to its mole fraction."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "$p_A = p_A^0 \\cdot x_A$"
    },
    {
      "type": "h3",
      "content": "Ideal vs Non-Ideal Solutions"
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "ordered": false,
      "items": [
        "<b>Ideal Solution:</b> Obeys Raoult’s law, no heat change",
        "<b>Non-Ideal Solution:</b> Shows deviation (positive or negative)"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "h2",
      "content": "Colligative Properties"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "These properties depend only on number of solute particles, not their nature."
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "ordered": false,
      "items": [
        "<b>Relative Lowering of Vapor Pressure:</b> $\\frac{\\Delta p}{p^0} = x_B$",
        "<b>Elevation in Boiling Point:</b> $\\Delta T_b = K_b \\cdot m$",
        "<b>Depression in Freezing Point:</b> $\\Delta T_f = K_f \\cdot m$",
        "<b>Osmotic Pressure:</b> $\\Pi = CRT$"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "h2",
      "content": "Abnormal Molar Mass"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "Due to <b>association</b> or <b>dissociation</b> of solute particles, observed molar mass differs."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "Van’t Hoff factor: $i = \\frac{observed\\ value}{normal\\ value}$"
    },
    {
      "type": "h2",
      "content": "Van’t Hoff Factor"
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "ordered": false,
      "items": [
        "i > 1 → Dissociation (e.g., NaCl)",
        "i < 1 → Association (e.g., acetic acid)",
        "i = 1 → No change"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "callout",
      "style": "warning",
      "icon": "fas fa-exclamation-triangle",
      "title": "Important for NEET",
      "content": "Focus on formulas of colligative properties and Van’t Hoff factor. Numerical questions are very common from this chapter."
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "headers": [
        "Property",
        "Formula",
        "Depends On"
      ],
      "rows": [
        [
          "Boiling Point Elevation",
          "$\\Delta T_b = K_b m$",
          "Molality"
        ],
        [
          "Freezing Point Depression",
          "$\\Delta T_f = K_f m$",
          "Molality"
        ],
        [
          "Osmotic Pressure",
          "$\\Pi = CRT$",
          "Concentration"
        ]
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "callout",
      "style": "success",
      "icon": "fas fa-check-circle",
      "title": "Quick Revision Trick",
      "content": "Remember: <b>‘Colligative = Count of particles’</b> → Only number matters, not nature."
    }
  ]
}